Lizards ğŸ¦drop their tails as a defense mechanism when threatened. This is because the tail contains a weak point, or a "fracture plane," which allows it to break off easily. When a predator grabs onto the lizard's tail, it will detach, allowing the lizard to escape while the predator is left holding onto the tail. Additionally, the detached tail will continue to wriggle and move, distracting the predator and giving the lizard time to get away. While the lizard can regrow its tail over time, it will never be the same as the original. ğŸ“¸Credits by @doctorazo Tag me on your posts if you are an amateur wildlife photographerğŸ¯ DMğŸ“¥ me for paid promotions/ads Follow us!!!
